What I Genuinely Dislike (v3 Specific)
The forecast is embarrassingly simple. avg_daily * 30 is spreadsheet math. You have 90 days of time-series data and access to ML.FORECAST. The gap between "what this could do" and "what it actually does" is the single most visible weakness. A Snowflake SA will spot this in 5 seconds.

Cost Intelligence is a black box. 1,070 lines of correlation logic with no tests and no confidence scoring. When it says "this change caused the cost spike," how does the user know it's not a coincidence? Correlation without causation confidence is dangerous — it gives false certainty.

You built the autoload framework but didn't fully deploy it. SUMMARY_AUTOLOAD_QUERY_BUDGET = 1 exists. The boundary is registered. But the forecast view, the annual projection, and other evidence views still use buttons. The infrastructure is ahead of the implementation. Ship the UX change.

The trajectory is positive but the foundation gap remains. Scores went up across the board, which is good. But the Critical-risk item (no pre-aggregation) has persisted across three reviews. Every feature built on top of direct ACCOUNT_USAGE queries is a feature that will break or timeout at scale. The longer this debt persists, the more expensive the migration becomes.

Bottom line for v3: This is now clearly a principal-architect-level project with genuine analytical sophistication (Cost Intelligence, Metric Registry, change-correlation). The score trajectory (+5 overall, +6 architecture) is healthy. The single biggest risk is that the pre-aggregation debt compounds with every new feature, and the single biggest missed opportunity is that the forecast uses arithmetic averaging when ML.FORECAST is available in the same platform.
